observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to enforce the following:

All accountable officials and employees concerned to comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 and Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and liquidate or refund immediately the cash advances granted to them, otherwise the necessary sanction for its settlement such as withholding of salary to be applied to the unliquidated cash advances shall be enforced or the penal provisions of Section 128 of PD No. 1445 be applied;

The Municipal Accountant should stop the granting of additional cash advances to officials and employees with previous cash accountabilities and to attach a certification on the grant of a new cash advance that previous cash advances of the concerned accountable officers were liquidated;

The Municipal Accountant to verify the unliquidated cash advances of officials and employees who are already separated from service and recommend for write-off upon sufficient proof that collection thereof is no longer feasible, pursuant to existing guidelines issued by the Commission on Audit;

Department Heads concerned to undertake measures/ action to compel the settlement of outstanding cash advances of those officials and employees who are still connected with the Municipality such as withholding of salary or other applicable penal sanctions; and

The Municipal Accountant to furnish to the Audit Team a copy of the issued demand letters to accountable officers with outstanding cash advances for review, verification and appropriate action.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the following: 

Petty Cash Custodian to monitor regularly the payment of the Petty Cash Fund and replenish it when disbursements therefrom reach at least 75% or as needed to ensure that the fund is sufficient to cover the petty operating expenses of the Municipality;

Petty Cash Custodian to record all the necessary information in the cashbook to facilitate immediate tracking and comparing of recorded transactions with the respective paid petty vouchers;

Officials / Employees concerned to revise the existing guidelines/ policies on the use of the Petty Cash Fund and include all the necessary details to ensure efficiency, economy and effectiveness in the disbursement of government funds; and

Submit the lacking documentary requirements enumerated in the attached schedule to avoid suspension or disallowance in audit.
We also recommended and Management agreed that the number of Petty Cash Funds and Petty Cash Custodians be reduced to implement a more effective internal control system on cash and the establishment and utilization of these funds should comply with the requirements of COA Circular No. 97-002.

We recommended the following:

