b) The Municipal Accountant prepare and maintain complete Supply Ledger Cards, and conduct periodic reconciliation with the property/supply records;

c) The Municipal Treasurer prepare and maintain complete Stock Cards, and conduct periodic reconciliation with the accounting records;

d) The Municipal Accountant to observe the Perpetual Inventory Method by initially recording the purchases of supplies and materials as Inventory, and subsequently recognize the same as expenses upon issuance/distribution to end-users/intended beneficiaries;

e) . . .; and

f) The Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant coordinate with the Rural Health Unit relative to the proper monitoring and recording of COVID-19 vaccines and ancillaries and other medical supplies and materials received from various source agencies. Also, make representations with source agencies on the cost of supplies/inventories as basis for recording in the books of accounts of the LGU.

We reiterated the following recommendations that the Municipal Accountant:

a) Exert extra efforts to trace prior years’ records including financial statements, trial balances, ledgers and/or supporting schedules to determine the unidentified beginning balances of subject liability accounts;

b) . . .

We recommended that Management:

a) Ensure optimal utilization of the 20 per cent Development Fund and proper implementation of development projects funded under said fund to achieve the desirable socio-economic targets and outcomes of the LGU;

b) Direct the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) in coordination with the Municipal Development Council (MDC) to ensure that the identified projects to be included in the AIP which are sourced from the 20 per cent Development Fund are well-planned and procurement-and-implementation-ready;

c) Direct the MPDC to provide for the specific timeframe or timing of implementation for each development project rather than a uniform and generic timeframe such as January to December of a calendar year for all identified projects; and initiate the procurement procedures of these projects earlier during the calendar year rather than towards the end of the year to avoid delays and/or non-implementation of projects;

d) Consider the reprogramming of continuing appropriations of unimplemented projects which may no longer be needed into other priority development projects; and

e) Revert the unexpended balances of continuing appropriations for fully completed projects to the unappropriated surplus of the general fund so that the same shall be made available for other priority development projects of the LGU.

We recommended the following:

a) The Local Chief Executive, thru the Human Resource Management Officer (HRMO), formulate a uniform policy or guidelines in the hiring of JO/COS personnel taking into consideration the LGU’s existing organizational structure, plantilla of personnel, service requirements, financial capability and existing COA, CSC and DBM rules and regulations; and endorse the same to the Office of the Sangguniang Bayan for legislation;

b) The Sangguniang Bayan, upon review and deliberation, institutionalize the policy or guidelines in the hiring of JO/COS personnel by legislating it into an ordinance;

c) The Management require the recording of attendance of all JO/COS personnel in permanent logbooks indicating their names and signatures as well as the time of arrival at and departure from their place of assignment;

d) The HRMO, in coordination with respective Heads of Offices/Departments, properly monitor and validate the attendance and actual accomplishments of JO/COS personnel; 

e) The Local Chief Executive and/or the Municipal Vice Mayor use the appropriate form of or type of contract or agreement in the hiring of JO personnel which includes the signature of the concerned JO personnel as acceptance or acknowledgment of the stipulations of the job order contract or agreement;

f) The Management pay the services of JO personnel using a daily salary rate taking into consideration the actual number of working days in a month; and

g) The HRMO carry out a periodic orientation/reorientation for JO/COS personnel on various rules and regulations on human resource, as well as, the terms and agreements of their employment.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the BAC to require the contractors to submit the DOLE-approved CSHP for the above infrastructure projects to the Audit Team. Prospectively, it shall ensure the submission of DOLE-approved CSHP for all infrastructure projects as an integral part of the contract as required by Item 37.2.3 (g) of the RIRR of RA 9184;
Require the BAC and the TWG to carefully evaluate all bid proposals such that detailed breakdown of estimates and/or unit cost analysis/derivation for each work item expressed in volume/area/lump sum/lot, particularly for CSHP, will be strictly required in accordance with COA Circular 2012-001;
Direct the Municipal Engineer to closely monitor the proper implementation of the Occupational Safety and Health Standards and Programs in each construction project to ensure the safety of every worker employed therein, as well as the general public; and
initiate the reporting of contractors found violating the safety rules and regulations to the Philippine Contractors Accreditation Board (PCAB) pursuant to Section 29 of the DOLE DO No. 198, series of 2018.

We recommended the following:
The Management shall refrain from acquisition of goods and services by way of cash advance. Instead, all procurement transactions shall be submitted to the BAC for evaluation and determination of the appropriate mode of procurement whether to use public bidding or other alternative modes of procurement;
The BAC shall ensure timely and proper posting of bid opportunity/ Request for Quotation (RFQ), Notice of Award, Contract and PO at the PHILGEPS website for transactions undertaken through alternative procurement which exceeded the threshold of ₱50,000.00;
The BAC shall conduct careful evaluation of the legal, financial, and technical capability of all suppliers by ensuring that the suppliers are registered with the PHILGEPS and shall require the submission of eligibility documents such as PHILGEPS registration, Mayors’/Business Permit, and Omnibus Sworn Statement, as applicable;
On reference to branding, the LCE shall direct all requisitioning departments to only include the technical specifications of items requested and exclude the brand names in the PRs prepared;
Prospectively, the Management ensure strict compliance with the provisions of the RIRR of RA 9184 for all procurement transactions of the Municipality.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the heads/concerned personnel of the offices with motor vehicles and heavy equipment assigned to ensure that preparation and submission of the Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption and Official Travels of the vehicles/equipment used by their sections for consolidation by the General Services Officer; and
Require the General Services Officer to submit regularly to the Audit Team the consolidated Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption and Official Travels for audit and verification purposes;

We recommended that Management instruct:
The Inventory Committee to ensure the conduct of the required annual  physical inventory of PPEs;
The Inventory Committee to ensure the conduct of the required annual  physical inventory of PPEs;
The Inventory Committee to submit the RPCPPE to the Audit Team, based on the results of physical inventory of PPEs;
The GSO to expedite and complete the process of consolidation of all the necessary reports relative to the conduct of one-time cleansing of PPE account balances;
The GSO to submit the pertinent reports and documents relative to the conduct of one-time cleansing of PPE account to the Municipal Accountant for reconciliation;
The Municipal Accountant to effect the necessary adjustment in the   PPE accounts and fairly present the balances in the LGU books, based on the reports and documents prepared by the GSO;
The Municipal Accountant ensure that the total balance of PPELCs tally with the controlling PPE accounts in the General Ledger, to establish proper reconciliation of records.

We recommended that:
The Municipal Accountant draw the following journal entries, in order to revert the amount of CIP directly closed to the Due to National Government Agencies and Trust Liability – Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund accounts, to wit:
The Municipal Accountant and Municipal Engineer to reconcile their records and reports and properly identify those completed and on-going projects;
The Municipal Engineer to furnish the Municipal Accountant all the pertinent documents to support the reclassification of CIP accounts by the Municipal Accountant;
The Municipal Accountant to draw the necessary journal entries reclassifying the CIP accounts to its appropriate PPE accounts, for projects which are already completed.

We recommended that:
The Municipal Accountant to immediately record those book reconciling items representing unrecorded disbursements, payrolls and debit memo properly supported with documents;
All the department heads to initiate the sending of confirmation letters, duly signed by the Local Chief Executive, to their counterpart national government agencies (DILG, DENR, DA, DSWD, DBM) to verify the existence of any liquidated fund transfers in the past which were received by the LGU for a specific purpose and could possibly correspond to the unrecorded credit memo in the previous years;
The Municipal Accountant to continue making representations with the banks in order to secure copies of the credit and debit memo, especially for those newly incurred credits and charges in CY 2023, so as to obtain proper bases and valid supporting documents to record the afore-cited reconciling items in the LGU books;
The Municipal Accountant to immediately record the amount representing the unrecorded credit memo after confirming with the national government agencies of the absence of any unliquidated fund transfers and exerting concrete efforts in order to determine the source agency of the bank credits, in order to utilize such amount for other beneficial programs and projects.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
Trace the payments made in the previous years to the bank pertaining to MDFO Loans;
Trace the transaction relative to payment of penalties totaling ₱136,439.11, identify the cause for the incurrence of penalties and furnish the Audit Team copies of documents relative thereto, for further evaluation.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
Review the journal entries and in coordination with the Municipal Treasurer, trace the discrepancy of ₱16,519.83 between Real Property Tax Receivable and Special Education Tax Receivables, as well as Deferred Real Property Tax and Deferred Special Education Tax;
Draw the necessary adjusting journal entry in order to reflect the correct amount of Real Property Tax and Special Education Tax Receivables and Deferred Real Property Tax and Deferred Special Education Tax.

We recommended that:
The Municipal Accountant identify excess funds which are due for remittance to source agencies;
The Municipal Accountant prepare the necessary reclassification entries to properly record those accounts which are due to LGUs and NGAs;
The Municipal Treasurer immediately process the payments to other LGUs for accounts which are already due remittance.

We recommended that:
The Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer and concerned department heads observe the provisions of COA Circular 94-013 in the timely liquidation of funds received;
The Municipal Treasurer immediately remit the shares of NGAS from LGU collections which are long overdue.

We recommended  that:
The Municipal Engineer submit the Statement of Work Accomplished and Certificate of Completion to prove project completion, as reported in the Reports on Government Project;
The Municipal Accountant and Municipal Engineer submit an explanation on the return of unexpended amount to the National Treasury despite claim of the Municipal Engineer on the 100% project completion per Report on Government Projects.

We recommended that Management:
Submit a written explanation on the non-utilization of the unexpended amount of funds received from DILG;
Require the MSWDO and MDDRMO to immediately identify the affected families of Typhoon Odette who were not yet given any financial assistance by the LGU or are in most need of any financial assistance and immediately facilitate the distribution of financial assistance to these families;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to record the distribution of financial assistance and immediately cause the liquidation of financial assistance.

We recommended that:
Management install a strong internal control over inventory management of hospital inventory items, whether locally funded or acquired thru donation, through proper discussion with the Municipal Hospital Administrator and other concerned LGU personnel, in order to safeguard assets against deterioration and expiration, and loss or wastage through illegal or improper disposition, to ensure efficiency, economy and effectiveness in the operations of government;
The Hospital Administrator immediately furnish the Municipal Accountant copies of all documents pertaining to receipt of donated inventory items for transparency and to facilitate recording thereof in the LGU books so as to fairly present the appropriate inventory accounts in the financial statements;
The Hospital Administrator coordinate with the PHO with regard to donated drugs and medicines which are already expired in the custody of SMH.

We recommended the following:
The Management assign personnel to exert efforts specifically in tracing back prior years’ transactions and records, and identify the unidentified reconciling items to reconcile the balances between the book and the bank pertaining to the LBP account nos. 0522-1114-30 and 0522-1145-29;
The Municipal Accountant prepare the necessary journal entries to record the identified book reconciling items;
Prepare the necessary journal entries to record the amounts of stale checks. Henceforth, the Municipal Accountant carefully review and analyze checks issued which have become stale at year-end and prepare the corresponding entries to reflect the correct Cash in Bank account balances as at year-end; and
Request for copies of bank statements for the subject cash in bank accounts which incurred dormancy charges as basis for the recording of adjusting entries to reflect the same and the correct Cash in Bank account balances as at year-end.

We recommended the following:
The Municipal Treasurer furnish the Municipal Accountant at the beginning of the year a duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year which will serve as basis of the latter for the booking up of the RPT and SET Receivable accounts;
The Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant undertake periodic reconciliation of the balances per master list of RPT delinquencies with that of the RPT and SET Receivable account balances per books of accounts to come up with a more accurate and proper balance of RPT and SET Receivable accounts;
The Municipal Accountant exert effort to identify the discrepancies of the reciprocal accounts, reconcile the same, and effect the necessary adjustments, as warranted, to reflect the correct account balances for fair presentation of accounts in the financial statements; and
The Municipal Accountant submit to the Office of the Auditor the Journal Entry Voucher to set up the RPT and SET Receivables together with the certified list of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year.

We recommended that:
The Municipal Accountant observe the Perpetual Inventory Method by initially recording the purchases of supplies and materials as inventory, and subsequently recognize the same as expenses upon issuance/distribution to end-users/intended beneficiaries;
The General Services Officer take control and custody of supplies and materials, and comply with the prescribed procedures in the requisition and issuance of inventory items, including the preparation of the RIS to support every issuance of supplies and inventories to requisitioning units or end-users, and the preparation and submission of the SSMI to the Accounting Office as basis for the recording of related expenses;
The Municipal Accountant prepare and maintain complete Supply Ledger Cards, and conduct periodic reconciliation with the property/supply records; and
The General Services Officer prepare and maintain complete Stock Cards, and conduct periodic reconciliation with the accounting records.

We recommended the following:
The Municipal Accountant, Inventory Committee and General Services Officer identify the variances of PPE account balances between the accounting records and the result of the physical count, and reconcile such variances to facilitate the proper recording/reporting of PPE account balances in the books of accounts of the LGU;
The Inventory Committee include in the physical count and the RPCPPE other PPE items such as, but not limited to, land, land improvements, infrastructure assets particularly road networks and water supply systems, and construction in progress accounts;
The Municipal Accountant determine the accuracy and validity of the public infrastructure assets reported in its Registry of Public Infrastructures, and make necessary adjustments in the LGU’s books of accounts to record the same, if warranted;
The Municipal Accountant prepare the necessary adjusting entries to record the costs of donated farm machineries and equipment, based on the confirmation reply of the Resident Auditor of DA-PhilMECH, and its accumulated depreciation, taking into consideration the date of receipt of the same;
The Municipal Accountant, with the assistance of the Municipal Engineer, make representation with the DPWH 2nd DEO, Guipos, Zamboanga del Sur, relative to the project turnover documents including cost information of the rehabilitated municipal hall building as basis for the recording of the same in the books of accounts of the LGU;
The General Services Officer prepare and maintain complete Property Cards, and periodically reconcile the same with the accounting records and the results of the physical count; and
The Municipal Accountant prepare and maintain complete PPE Ledger Cards, and periodically reconcile the same with the property records and the results of the physical count.

We recommended that:
The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Engineer conduct reconciliation of documents/records pertaining to the Construction in Progress accounts;
The Municipal Engineer furnish the Municipal Accountant copies of the certificate of completion, approved program of works and other pertinent documents as basis for the reclassification of accounts for completed projects;
The Municipal Accountant identify all costs incurred for each project based on the approved program of works and other relevant documents, and make the necessary adjustments to reclassify the completed projects into their appropriate PPE accounts; and
The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Engineer establish a proper monitoring system particularly for projects undertaken by administration in order for the former to completely record all costs incurred thereto as CIP accounts during construction, and to reclassify the total costs incurred into the appropriate PPE account after its completion.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
Exert extra efforts to trace prior years’ records including financial statements, trial balances, ledgers and/or supporting schedules to determine the unidentifiable beginning balances of the subject liability accounts;
Request for write-off of the dormant Due to NGAs account balances in accordance with existing COA rules and regulations;
Determine the validity of unremitted balances to GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth and cause the immediate remittance or adjustments of the same, as warranted;
Make representations with concerned government agencies relative to the abnormal/negative account balances and the refund and/or other appropriate actions for over-remittances made. In case refund is not granted and no other course of action can be taken, the official responsible refund the said amounts; and
Properly monitor the withholding and remittance of mandatory contributions/obligations so as to avoid under/over-remittance of the same; and review thoroughly the schedule of payables due to concerned agencies during the month and ensure that remittances are based on actual contributions vis-a-vis payroll deductions made.
We further recommended that Management, thru the Human Resource Management Officer, compel concerned officials and employees to register and/or update their accounts with GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth in order for the Municipal Accountant to proceed with the remittance of the mandatory obligations withheld from their salaries and to avoid the incurrence of penalties/surcharges due to non-remittance. In case of failure of concerned officials and employees to register and/or update their accounts, any penalties/surcharges imposed by concerned government agencies be charged against them.

We recommended that:
Management take full opportunity on the application of COA Circular No. 2020-006 and fully comply with the prescribed guidelines and procedures, particularly the conduct of physical count of PPE, the recognition of PPE items found at station, the disposition of non-existing/missing PPE items, the procedures in the derecognition of non-existing/missing PPEs without available record of accountability, and the recording of accounting entries and disclosures in the notes to financial statements, for the purpose of one-time cleansing of PPE account balances of the LGU;
The Local Chief Executive reconstitute or supplement the LGU’s existing Inventory Committee to include at least one regular employee from the Accounting Office and designate a committee head or chairperson;
The Inventory Committee prepare the PIP, to be approved by the local chief executive and submit the approved PIP to the Office of the Auditor at least ten (10) calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory taking activities;
The Property Unit prepare the List of PPEs Found at Station in accordance with the prescribed format provided in Annex B of the Circular, establish or assign a unit cost/value for each PPE item in coordination with the LGU’s Appraisal Committee, prepare property cards for PPE items found at station, and submit the list to the Municipal Accountant as basis for the recording in the books of accounts; and
The Property Unit prepare a List of Non-Existing/Missing PPEs (Annex C of the Circular) and follow the procedures for the disposition of the non-existing/missing PPE items provided under Sections 7 and 8 of the Circular, as applicable.

We recommended the following:
The General Services Officer (GSO) prepare the IIRUP in its prescribed form, and submit the same to the Disposal Committee for inspection, appraisal and disposal of the identified unserviceable properties. The GSO coordinate with the Municipal Accountant in providing relevant information in the IIRUP such as the cost, accumulated depreciation, accumulated impairment losses, if any, carrying amount and other remarks for each unserviceable property;
The Management, thru the Local Chief Executive, create a Disposal Committee whose functions include the inspection, appraisal and disposal of unserviceable properties in accordance to COA and DBM Joint Circular No. 2024-1 dated January 30, 2024;
The Disposal Committee, after its creation, conduct inspection and appraisal and set the final appraised values of all unserviceable properties subject for disposal, as identified and reported in the IIRUP. The appraised values shall be considered as the minimum selling price so that the LGU will receive fair compensation for the items sold;
The Management submit to the Office of the Auditor a written letter, together with the IIRUP, appraisal report and other pertinent documents, requesting for technical evaluation of the appraised values of the unserviceable properties as determined by the Disposal Committee, which will be endorsed by the latter to the COA IX Technical Audit Group for their independent evaluation; and
The Disposal Committee determine the appropriate mode of disposal and undertake the disposal proceedings in accordance with the revised manual on the disposal of government properties.

We recommended that Management:
Ensure optimal utilization of the 20 per cent Development Fund and proper implementation of development projects funded under said fund to achieve the desirable socio-economic targets and outcomes of the LGU;
Direct the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) in coordination with the Municipal Development Council (MDC) to ensure that the identified projects to be included in the AIP which are sourced from the 20 per cent Development Fund are well-planned and procurement-and-implementation-ready;
Direct the MPDC to properly identify and specify the existing loans of the LGU in the AIP and provide proper estimates of appropriations for each loan based on the schedules of loan amortizations to avoid over-estimation or over-allocation of appropriations for the same;
Direct the MPDC to provide for the specific timeframe or timing of implementation for each development project rather than a uniform and generic timeframe such as January to December of a calendar year for all identified projects;
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to properly monitor and control the appropriations and obligations incurred in order to avoid erroneous charges of expenditures;
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to review the obligations incurred for the Upgrading from Gravel to PCCP of Brgy. Poblacion to Lake Dasay, Brgy. Sayog Road Section funded in CY 2022 and the Concreting of Junction Barangay Lantawan Road to Elementary School funded in CY 2021, and prepare the necessary adjustments to reflect the correct balances of unobligated appropriations;
Consider the reprogramming of continuing appropriations of unimplemented projects which may no longer be needed into other priority development projects; and
Revert the unexpended balances of continuing appropriations for fully completed projects to the unappropriated surplus of the general fund so that the same be made available for other priority development projects of the LGU.

We recommended that Management:
Coordinate with the Provincial Government of Zamboanga del Sur regarding the revision of the MOA or preparation of supplemental MOA to clarify or expound the provision on the purpose of the procured heavy equipment funded out of the LDRRM Fund including the processes involved in cases when the contract will be rescinded, and the turn-over procedures and accounting treatment for the same in the books of the Provincial Government and the Municipality;
Coordinate with the Provincial Government of Zamboanga del Sur on the submission of documents pertaining to the turn-over of the heavy equipment as proof that the ownership was transferred by the Province of Zamboanga del Sur to the Municipality of San Miguel;
Require the Municipal Accountant to record the heavy equipment in the books of the Municipality on the basis of the turn-over documents submitted by the Provincial Government of Zamboanga del Sur; and
Submit to the audit team the revised or supplemental MOA, turn-over documents and any related documents once these are already available.

We recommended that Management:
Revisit its existing Local Revenue Code and update/improve provisions and rates/fees indicated therein, by enacting a municipal ordinance through its Sanggunian Bayan, including, but not limited to, the rental of personal and real properties owned by the Municipality. Henceforth, submit a copy of the updated Local Revenue Code to the Office of the Auditor;
Modify/amend the rental fees under the lease contracts in accordance with the existing/updated Local Revenue Code, as applicable;
Enter into lease contracts with concerned lessees who have assumed the spaces/stalls occupied by previous individuals/businesses without entering into lease agreement with the LGU and submit the same to the Office of the Auditor together with the noted unsubmitted lease contracts;
Issue demand letters to concerned lessees and enforce collections of unpaid rentals, and/or cause the termination/cancellation of the contracts if, without justifiable reasons, the lessees fail to make payments of their unpaid rental fees. Henceforth, intensify the collection efforts of the rental fees through the Municipal Treasurer’s Office; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary adjustments to record the uncollected town center rental fees. Henceforth, properly account receivables and earned income on town center rentals in the LGU’s books of accounts.

For the subsequent implementation of similar programs/projects, we recommended that:
The Municipal Agriculturist include in the activity/program designs the basis or criteria for the identification and selection of qualified beneficiaries;
The Local Chief Executive enter into a Memorandum of Agreement with concerned associations in its implementation of programs/projects which requires the participation of the latter;
The Management, thru the Municipal Agriculturist, require the concerned partner-associations relative to the animal dispersal program to enter into agreements with the identified beneficiaries, laying out the conditions and responsibilities of the beneficiaries for the grants received by them; and
The Management, thru the Municipal Agriculturist, require the concerned partner-associations and beneficiaries to submit beneficiary profile and/or proof of identification that the beneficiaries are bona fide members of the said associations.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to
(a) send demand letters to AOs and employees concerned requiring them to refund/liquidate their outstanding cash advances;
(b) require the Human Resources and Management Office (HRMO) to withhold the payment of salary/benefits due the active AOs concerned;
(c) institute available legal remedies and sanctions that may apply pursuant to COA Circular No. 97-002; and
(d) require the MA to (i) submit subsidiary records for the unaccounted cash advances amounting to ₱200,000.00; and (ii) strictly comply with the regulations on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances.

We recommended and the LCE require the
(a) ME, BAC Chairperson, and MA to
(i) determine and address the cause of the deficiencies pertaining to the supporting documents; and
(ii) submit the documents on the noted transactions with deficiencies on supporting documents;
(b) ME to
(i) coordinate with the Contractors concerned for the installation of project signboards on noted projects;
(ii) require the Contractors to immediately post the warranty security for completed infrastructure projects in accordance with the Section 62 of the 2016 RIRR of RA No. 9184;
(iii) issue variation or change order to cover increase or decrease in quantities as a result of disparity between the preconstruction plans and construction drawings after the award of the contract; and
(iv) for projects with discrepancies in the actual measurement, submit as-built plans to reflect the changes made in the original contract;
(c) BAC Chairperson to subject all procurements to public bidding unless the conditions are met for the use of alternative mode of procurements; and
(d) MA to
(i) account for the excess of the BOQ and the negative slippage and compute for the liquidated damages to be charged to the Contractor concerned for not satisfactorily completing the work at Barangay Biclat within the specified contract time;
(ii) ensure that the advance payment of 15% of the contract price is supported with written request of the Contractor and irrevocable standby letter of credit of equivalent value from a commercial bank, a bank guarantee or a surety bond callable upon demand, issued by a surety or insurance company duly licensed by the Insurance Commission prior to payment to contractors; and
(iii) ensure that supporting documents are sufficient and valid before payment is made.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to require the
(a) BAC Chairperson/ Secretariat to
(i) post in the PhilGEPS the RFQ and Award for the procurements covered by the alternative mode of procurement – Shopping; and
(ii) issue BAC Resolutions recommending the use of alternative mode of procurement for approval of the LCE;
(b) MA, BAC Chairperson, and MDRRM Officer to submit the lacking documentary requirements which include list of recipients and pictures of actual distribution of welfare goods amounting to ₱597,600.00; proof of posting of RFQ in the PhilGEPS website, website of the Municipality, if available, and at any conspicuous place reserved for this purpose in the premises of the Municipality; OSS and latest ITR of noted transactions, among others; and
(c) MA to
(i) transfer the unexpended DRRMF under the account “Trust Liability - DRRM” in the Trust Fund books at year-end;
(ii) prepare the necessary adjustments to reflect the correct balances of Welfare Goods Expense and Disaster Response and Rescue Equipment at year-end;
(iii) submit on a monthly basis the Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF; and
(iv) ensure that the necessary documents supporting payment claims are valid and complete before payment is made to suppliers.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to require the
(a) HRMO to strictly enforce the use of biometrics system and ensure that the payroll at period-end is supported with the biometrics-generated DTRs;
(b) impose salary deductions for absences incurred by personnel;
(c) update and correct the personnel records to reflect accurate information on the spelling of names and date of birth of personnel; and
(d) attach a certification stating that the activities/services of JO personnel cannot be provided by regular or permanent personnel of the Municipality to support the first claim of JOs pursuant to paragraph 4.1.3 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012.

We recommended the following:

a) The Inventory Committee conduct annually a complete physical count of PPE to facilitate the preparation and submission of RPCPPE not later than January 31 of each year, complete with all the required information, which shall serve as the basis for the reconciliation and updating of accounting and property records;

b) . . .; 

c) . . .; and

d) The Municipal Accountant determine the accuracy and validity of the public infrastructure assets reported in its Registry of Public Infrastructures, and make necessary adjustments in the LGU’s books of accounts to record the same, if warranted.

We recommended that the BAC comply with the pertinent provisions under the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 pertaining to the application of Negotiated Procurement – Two Failed Biddings, taking into consideration the following courses of action:

a) Ensure that Invitations to Bid pertaining to the first and second public bidding are posted in the PhilGEPS website;

b) Prepare separate BAC Resolutions declaring first and second failure of bidding indicating the reason for the failure;

c) Prepare BAC Resolution recommending alternative method of procurement of Negotiated Procurement – Two Failed Biddings, for approval of the Head of the Procuring Entity;

d) Prepare Request for Quotations and post the same in the PhilGEPS website and at any conspicuous place reserved for this purpose in the premises of the Procuring Entity for a period of at least three (3) calendar days;

e) Invite observers during procurement proceedings in accordance with Section 13 of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;

f) Post the Notice of Award, Purchase Order/Contract and Notice to Proceed in the PhilGEPS website and at any conspicuous place reserved for this purpose in the premises of the Procuring Entity within ten (10) days from their issuance;

g) Require suppliers to submit their PhilGEPS Certificate of Registration and Membership if legal eligibility requirements are not subject to revision after the conduct of the mandatory review

h) Require suppliers to post performance securities in the form prescribed under Section 39.2 of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184; and

i) Impose warranty securities after acceptance of goods in the form prescribed under Section 62.1 of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184.

We recommended further that the Municipal Accountant ensure completeness of the documentary requirements relative to procurements undertaken thru Negotiated Procurement – Two Failed Biddings before disbursements for such procurements are processed and paid.

We recommended that Management:

a)	Assign personnel to exert effort specifically in tracing back prior years’ transactions and records, and identify the reconciling items to reconcile the balances between the book and the bank pertaining to the LBP account nos. 0522-1114-30 and 0522-1145-29. Also, make representation with concerned depository banks for copies of bank statements particularly those of previous years;

b)	Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary journal entries to record the identified book reconciling items;

